Here is just someone who is fixing my kitchen floor. And I'm pretending right now that I still have a job and am working from home while I sit on Too Hot to Handle.
If I could damn well manage to open the file. (F*** One Drive.)
*Hackers voice* I'm in.
And that's exactly where he starts, drilling super loud. Hurrah.
It feels uncomfortably passive-aggressive to crank my air purifier all the way up, but I can smell the wood dust, so it would actually be completely okay even if he weren't a mask opponent. And do I really need to protect myself?
I would really like to go back to bed, but I can't until he's gone.
At least I have finally finished revising Chapter 4!
Chapter five is long, but so damn terrifying. Oh yeah, that's the good stuff!
I'm doing a search and replace for ... ➡️ ellipsis symbol and there are 54 in this chapter 😅
But no, I stick to my point. Natural language is mostly fragmented, especially when one becomes emotional.
The contractor is now at it with the vacuum cleaner. Hopefully, that means he'll be done soon.
He's gone out to cut something (or so it sounds). I secretly checked how far he is. There's still a lot to do :(
Only 7 pages left in Chapter 5. Still my favorite chapter and it's pretty decent – mainly changes to the text and very minor corrections in dialogue, and I need to rephrase everything a bit more concisely. But I could really use a break and a cup of tea right now, but the guy is still in my kitchen.
Now he's just started vacuuming dust again. Hopefully, that's a good sign.
The kitchen guy is gone!
He told me he had given them a quote for the entire floor, but the landlords were too cheap and only paid for the part next to the door that wasn't in order. Feels so much better.
The house is being ventilated and my air purifier is running in the kitchen while I'm having tea in the garden!
